. Community Programming for System- Impacted Latinas -- t11. From the Streets to the Halls of Higher Education: The Case of an Undocumented Latina on the Margins of the Justice System -- t12. Maternal Racial and Ethnic Strategies as a Protective Factor against Delinquency among Latina Girls: An Exploratory Study -- t13. Mi Hermana’s Keeper: Empowering Latina Youth to Improve Services That Prevent Juvenile Justice System Involvement -- t14. Xinachtli: A Healing- Informed, Gendered, and Culturally Responsive Approach with System- Involved Latinas -- tConclusion -- tAbout the Contributors -- tAbout the Editors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHow Latina girls and women become entangled in the criminal justice systemDespite representing roughly 16 percent of incarcerated women, Latina women and girls are often rendered invisible in accounts of American crime and punishment. In Latinas in the Criminal Justice System, Vera Lopez and Lisa Pasko bring together a group of distinguished scholars to provide a more complete, nuanced picture of Latinas as victims, offenders, and targets of deportation. Featuring Cecilia Menjívar, Lisa M. Martinez, Alice Cepeda, and others, this volume examines the complex histories, backgrounds, and struggles of Latinas in the criminal justice system. Contributors show us how Latinas encounter a variety of justice systems, including juvenile detention, adult court and corrections, and immigration and customs enforcement. Topics include Latina victims of crime and their perceptions of police officers; the impact of the US “crimmigration” system on undocumented Latina women; and help-seeking among Latina victims of intimate partner violence. Additionally, key chapters highlight the emergence of legal reforms, community mobilization efforts, and gender-sensitive alternatives to incarceration designed to increase equitable outcomes. Lopez and Pasko broaden our understanding of how gender, ethnicity, and legal status uniquely shape the experiences of system-impacted Latina girls and women. Latinas in the Criminal Justice System is a timely and much-needed resource for academics, activists, and policymakers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofzUnited States. 0aDiscrimination in criminal justice administrationzUnited States. 0aDiscrimination in law enforcementzUnited States. 0aFemale offenderszUnited States. 0aHispanic American womenxCrimes against. 0aWomen immigrantszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Hispanic American Studies.2bisacsh  aBorder policies.  aBullying.  aCarceral policies.  aCrimmigration.  aCulturally-responsive programming.  aDating violence.  aDeportation.  aDetention.  aEthnic identity.  aEthnicity.  aFamily.  aFemale delinquency.  aFeminist criminology.  aGang involvement.  aGangs.  aGender.  aGendered violence.  aImmigration Enforcement.  aImmigration.  aIncarcerated women.  aInterpersonal victimization.  aIntersectionality.  aIntimate partner victimization.  aIntimate partner violence.  aJuvenile justice.  aLatin America.  aLatina offenders.  aLatina youth.  aLeadership.  aMigration.  aMother-daughter relationship.  aMothering.  aPathways factors.  aPrevention.  aProtective factors.  aPunishment.  aSchooling.  aSexual assault.  aSexual minority girls.  aSmuggling.  aSocial justice.  aSocial networks.  aUS legal system.  aVictimization.  aViolence.  aYouth.1 aCano, Veronica E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCepeda, Alice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCreswell Báez, Johanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabula